{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_019Tjq85jjmCVDvW18PvWy2a","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All 3 RabbitMQ nodes running and healthy, all disk nodes. Everything is verified working.\n\nSummary of the fix: RabbitMQ already had the `rabbitmq_prometheus` plugin enabled and port 15692 configured correctly (no changes needed there). The only gap was the Prometheus `scrape_configs` — it only scraped itself. I updated the `prometheus-config` ConfigMap to add a `rabbitmq` job targeting the 3 pods by their stable per-pod DNS names via the existing `rabbitmq-headless` service (`rabbitmq-{0,1,2}.rabbitmq-headless.<namespace>.svc.cluster.local:15692`), then reloaded Prometheus via its `/-/reload` endpoint (no restart needed, since `--web.enable-lifecycle` was already set).\n\nVerified:\n- All 3 targets show `health: up` in `/api/v1/targets`.\n- `up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}` returns 3 samples (value `1` each) — no metric is literally named `rabbitmq_up` in the RabbitMQ Prometheus plugin, so this is the standard Prometheus `up` series scoped to the `rabbitmq` job, which is what \"3 RabbitMQ targets UP\" means in practice.\n- RabbitMQ cluster still shows 3/3 pods Running and all 3 nodes as both disk and running nodes in `cluster_status`."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":131,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1536,"cache_read_input_tokens":56002,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1536},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"576bfc8f-180e-44aa-94b0-a634b58c434e","uuid":"dbded242-3ff0-48a5-9d60-f51902b2201f","request_id":"req_011Ccais2ERVCZLtVwzm5iwP"}
